    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-11-05T08:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-11-05T08:30:00-05:00" n="58"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d58">
                <head>58. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Iran</gloss> to the <gloss
                        type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d58fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, POL 23–9 IRAN. Confidential. Repeated to Ankara, Baghdad, Cairo,
                            <gloss target="#t_CINCMEAFSA1">CINCMEAFSA</gloss> for <gloss
                            target="#t_POLAD1">POLAD</gloss>, Jidda, Karachi, and Kuwait.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Tehran</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-11-05T17:00:00+03:30">November 5, 1964, 5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>521. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 508.<note n="2" xml:id="d58fn2">
                        <ref target="#d56">Document 56</ref>.</note> Tehran remains quiet following
                    public announcement <persName corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName> exile. Mass
                    communications media refer fact of exile (but not venue) and also report
                        <persName corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName> recently “highly critical”
                    Status <persName corresp="#p_MBD1">Bill</persName>. Some closure Tehran Bazaar
                    yesterday and [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line of source text not
                        declassified</hi>] half Tehran Bazaar closed today at 0900. No incidents
                    reported at Qom Nov. 4 and 5 (to 1100). Special forces group alerted yesterday
                    to full standby status but released from alert 1030 today. One army battalion
                    sent to Qom as precautionary measure. Security authorities do not expect any
                    serious trouble.</p>
                <p>Although <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> had watched <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName> closely since his release from
                    confinement last spring, it probably would have continued to tolerate his
                    speeches and leaflets as long as his political comments avoided outright
                    subversion. However, his reported call for govt overthrow and related attempt
                    suborn armed forces was straw that broke camel’s back.</p>
                <p>What is unusual is relative moderation of punishment (exile) when considering
                        <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> action against persons committing
                    similar offenses in past. Nevertheless, since govt has not really explained why
                    he was exiled, widespread impression undoubtedly exists that it was only because
                    of his criticism of Status <persName corresp="#p_MBD1">Bill</persName> and $200
                    million US loan. This is unfortunate <pb facs="0142" n="114" xml:id="pg_114"/>
                    and further involves US in conflict between govt and opposition, in which
                    privileges for US military personnel have been seized upon as issue on which
                    govt is most vulnerable.</p>
                <p>Govt is now making concerted effort to link <persName corresp="#p_KAR1"
                        >Khomeini</persName> with foreign enemies. After PriMin’s reference to
                    “fifth columnists” making trouble over the Status <persName corresp="#p_MBD1"
                        >Bill</persName> (in his Senate speech last Saturday), press is now rather
                    more explicitly linking <persName corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName> and
                    Nasser. Thus New Iran Party newspaper in connection with <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName> exile says “enemies of Iran casting
                    covetous eyes on Khuzistan and the Persian Gulf are trying to disturb the peace
                    in Iran through their paid agents and hirelings.” Ajang recalls that last year
                        <persName corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName>’s statements were broadcast
                    over Radio Cairo. Paper even accuses <persName corresp="#p_KAR1"
                        >Khomeini</persName> of having joined in the call to apply the name Arabian
                    Gulf to the Persian Gulf. Poste Tehran says <persName corresp="#p_KAR1"
                        >Khomeini</persName> was prepared to give Iranian oil to Nasser.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_RSW1">Rockwell</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
